<head>
<title>Tools: Sharp Stuff</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">

<h1><font color="#008080"><font size="6">SHARP STUFF</font></font></h1>

<hr>

<p>With the spring pruning season now upon us, it might be a good
idea to get those pruners out and prepare them for the nice clean
cuts that both the plants and gardeners prefer. So what attention
should your pruning shears get? Generally a sharpening is called
for. A ragged pruning cut can encourage die back to occur. A nice
clean cut just above a bud-eye will ensure prompt healing. A good
cleaning and oiling of the bearings makes it easier on your hand
and wrist muscles. Plus the entire process shouldn't take more
than an hour or so once you get all your materials and tools
gathered. </p>

<p>These instructions are specific to Felco pruners: however the
same general guidelines apply to other pruners. Although a
pruning shear blade can be sharpened without taking the unit
completely apart, the disassembly of the entire unit makes it
lots easier to hone the cutting edge and also to clean any grit
or other debris that have accumulated in the bearings and on the
blade surfaces since the tool was last sharpened. (Can you
remember when?) The tools for the job at hand should be a screw
driver, a pair of pliers, and a sharpening stone. </p>

<p>After the unit has been disassembled, I would use a solvent
such as alcohol to clean the parts. In the case of the Felco
pruners, the blade can be completely detached from its mount. The
inset is a detached blade showing some evidence of a need for
sharpening. Depending on how pruners are used and cared for, the
edge may develop dull areas and even nicks. While the nicks in
your blades may not show up as vividly as those shown,
examination with a hand lens may reveal irregularities which must
be removed if clean pruning cuts are to be made. </p>

<p>In the sharpening process the only part of the blade that
should be ground with the sharpening stone is the beveled edge. </p>

<p>How long should you continue the grinding? Until the nicks and
dull areas have been eliminated. You can check this out with a
magnifier or by carefully feeling the edge with a very, very
light touch of your thumb. After the beveled edge has been ground
satisfactorily, one should stroke the flat side of the blade
several times to eliminate any burrs that may have formed during
the grinding. </p>

<p>In assembling the pruners, I tighten the bearing until just
before the friction prevents the spring from opening the blade.
This will ensure that there is a tight fit between the blade and
the opposing arm of the shears. A drop or two of oil should
complete the process To determine how well you've done, I suggest
a progressive 3-step test, which involves making cuts in: </p>

<ul>
    <li>a 3x5 file card </li>
    <li>a newspaper page </li>
    <li>a piece of kleenex. </li>
</ul>

<p>If you pass Step 1, you are probably okay, but I would
encourage more sharpening and adjusting until you reach at least
Step 2. If you pass the 3rd Step, you are a &quot;super
sharpener&quot;. </p>

<p><font color="#008080"><i>Bob Alde is the editor of the
Montgomery Master Gardener's and The Rose Society's newsletters.</i></font>
</p>

<p><font color="#008080"><i>Master Gardeners offer their services
in may horticultural endeavors. For more information about the
Montgomery County Master Gardeners Speakers Bureau, the special
children's program 'Close Encounters of the Agricultural Kind',
and the upcoming plant clinic schedule, please call (301)
590-9650.</i></font> </p>

<hr>

