<body background="../graphics/backgrd5.gif" link="#800000"
vlink="#FF8040">

<p><font size="6" face="Brush Script MT">From the</font><font
color="#800000" size="6" face="Brush Script MT"> Editors</font><font
size="6" face="Brush Script MT"> Desk</font><font size="6"> </font></p>

<blockquote>
    <p><img src="../graphics/writers/sk2b.jpg" width="240"
    height="209"></p>
</blockquote>

<blockquote>
    <h2><font size="4"><em><strong>Dear Readers</strong></em></font>,
    </h2>
    <p>Welcome to the beginning of our third year. The new year's
    first month has brought a knee high snowfall then torrential
    rains and flooding. Thankfully my only suffering involved an
    extra week of vacation with the children and a few missed
    deadlines. Some of my garden did not fare so well for Nature
    prunes without discrimination. Joann's article on winter
    storm survival may help your garden through the REST of the
    winter. </p>
    <p>February in this area's gardening community packs some
    hard choices on the lecture and show circuit. Check out the
    calendar for these listings. Attending a good lecture or
    flower show is a bit like getting lost in a new seed catalog:
    you end up dreaming of and planning for spring. The planning
    of a new garden is the most positive part of the experience.
    For it is, most times, completely devoid of error until the
    act of planting begins! Sylvia shares suggestions as to how
    selections manage to get on her order form. Jacqui excites us
    with enthusiastic raves about the National Garden Bureau's
    1996 Flower of the Year. T<i>ake care less you order all 10+
    varieties now available</i>. </p>
    <p>If your lawn is in desperate need of renovation or
    improvement we have lots of information on turfgrass care,
    selection and maintenance that we'll be sharing over the next
    few months. Early spring can be an opportune time to execute
    lawn improvements. </p>
    <p>Our contributing fruit expert has pointers on grafting and
    offers demonstrations during February and March however, keep
    a watchful eye on his covered waxpot. </p>
    <p>As a gardener, I often contemplate on how my yard provides
    a habitat for all sorts of life. From his recent newsletter,
    Tom Powell's commentary on our responsibility caught my eye
    and has been included for your consideration. </p>
    <p>In reference to attracting birds, even a yard full of
    berried shrubs, thickets and three sunflower-packed feeders
    cannot persuade songbirds to visit when a hawk has camped out
    in my backyard! The silence is eerie and foreboding. It is
    most unpleasant for in years past, February's prospect was
    more tolerable due to the hellebore's blooms, the birds'
    chatter, and, of course, the thought of March following! Till
    then! </p>
</blockquote>

<blockquote>
    <p><img src="../graphics/writers/sksig.gif" width="108"
    height="66"> </p>
    <p><a href="../flora/index.htm"><b>Sherry Kitchen</b></a>, <i>editor</i>
    </p>
</blockquote>

