<head>
<title>Garden Pests: Tick Fact Sheet</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body background="../graphics/backgrd5.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">

<h1><font color="#800000"><font size="6"><strong>Garden Pests</strong></font></font></h1>

<blockquote>
    <h2><font size="5"><strong>Tick Fact Sheet</strong></font></h2>
    <p>Ticks have become more well known in recent years due to
    the increasing number of Lyme disease cases. Most people
    encounter ticks either through contact with their pets or
    through outdoor recreational activities. Ticks can also be
    found living in landscaped lawns and gardens. </p>
    <p>The Northern deer tick is commonly found in the
    northeastern part of the United States. The nymphs of
    Northern deer ticks are the primary carries of Lyme disease.
    Between 30% and 80% of all Northern deer ticks are carriers
    of Lyme disease. Ticks carrying Lyme disease need to feed for
    12 to 24 hours before they can transmit it to people or pets.
    Check yourself and your pets frequently to reduce your chance
    of infection. </p>
    <p>A female tick lays approximately 2,500 eggs each spring.
    The larvae prefer to feed on a white-footed mouse. After
    molting, the adult ticks typically feed and mate on
    white-tail deer before they lay eggs and die in the fall. If
    the preferred mouse and deer hosts are unavailable, the ticks
    may be forced to feed and live on other animals such as dogs,
    cats, birds, or humans. Lyme disease is most commonly
    transmitted by the feeding nymphs in May and June. It's best
    to thoroughly examine your family members and pets after
    outings. Ticks hide in places where they can feed
    undisturbed, so be sure to check your head, armpits, groin,
    and clothing. Ticks may also hide in your pet's ears or
    between their toes so check those areas thoroughly too. If
    you locate an unattached tick, simply brush it off. You can
    dispose of it by drowning it in soapy water. If you locate an
    embedded tick, <b>do not panic</b>! Grasp the tick firmly by
    its head with a pair of tweezers. Apply steady, gradual
    pressure until the tick releases itself. Cleanse the site
    well and apply an antiseptic. </p>
    <p>People who have been infected with Lyme disease
    frequently, but not always, notice a reddish colored rash
    radiating from the location of the bite. Fatigue, stiff
    joints and flu-like symptoms may also accompany the rash. You
    should see a doctor as soon as possible if you suspect you
    have Lyme disease. If detected early, Lyme disease is usually
    treatable with antibiotics. </p>
    <h3><b><i>Avoid Lyme Disease:</i></b> </h3>
    <ul>
        <li>Tuck your pants into your socks to prevent ticks from
            climbing upward under your clothing. </li>
        <li>Place bird feeders away from your deck and house.
            Birds may carry ticks and mice may be attracted by
            dropped seed. </li>
        <li>Decrease the available nesting sites for mice. Keep
            grass mowed and woodpiles stacked away from your
            house. </li>
        <li>Wear light colored clothing when you enjoy the
            outdoors. Ticks are much easier to see against a
            light background. </li>
    </ul>
    <p><font color="#000000">According to the Maryland
    Cooperative Extension Services Home and Garden Information
    Center, all life stages of the black legged tick (formerly
    call the deer tick) are still active now. They do have tapes
    and publications available on this subject. Call
    1-800-342-2507 (within Maryland). </font></p>
</blockquote>

<h4><font color="#800000"><i>This information supplied by the IPM
Tick Fact Sheet published by the National Arboretum.(202)
245-5975.</i> </font></h4>

<p><font color="#800000"><b><i>© 1995 InSync Publishing. All
rights reserved. <br>
No material may be reprinted without written permission from the
publisher.</i></b> </font></p>

