<head>
<title>IPM: June's Pest Patrol</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body background="../graphics/backgrd5.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">

<h1><font color="#804000"><font size="6">IPM</font></font><font
size="6"> </font></h1>

<blockquote>
    <h1><font size="5">June's Pest Patrol</font></h1>
    <p>In June guard against Weevils, Lacebugs, and Borers. Look
    for notched leaf margins on the new growth of broadleaf
    evergreens, such as rhododendron, azaleas, and yews, for the
    signs of black vine weevil feeding. The adults are black,
    feed at night, and usually hide in leaf litter during the
    day. Heavy infestations may defoliate shrubs. It is the
    larvae that cause severe damage to the root system, causing
    girdling of crowns and wilting of the plant. Feeding occurs
    from midsummer into fall. Treat the soil beneath the plant
    with nematodes packaged in a product such as Biosafe to kill
    the larvae, or treat the top of the plant and soil with a
    residual insecticide, such as orthene to kill the adult
    weevils. </p>
    <p>June is also the time to check for azalea lacebug. They
    feed on the undersides of leaves, but damage is visible on
    the upper leaf surfaces. Previously damaged leaves will look
    white and stippled, much like mite damage from a distance.
    Turn the leaf over and check the underside for lacebug
    nymphs, along with the presence of brown patches, black fecal
    spots, and black eggs that are laid next to the leaf margins.
    Nymphs are black, wingless, and spiny looking. Control
    lacebugs early to prevent new foliage from becoming
    unsightly. Apply insecticidal soap, oil, or a systemic
    insecticide to newly hatched nymphs. Continue to monitor
    plants, even after treatment, because not all of the eggs may
    hatch at once. </p>
    <p>Sharp attention to pruning out any new watersprouts that
    emerge on dogwood trees will help prevent the spread of <i>Discula</i>
    anthracnose. Watersprouts can become infected and die,
    allowing the fungus to quickly spread to the main trunk. Once
    inside the main trunk the tree will probably die. If you have
    lost a dogwood to this deadly disease consider planting a
    Kousa dogwood or one of the new resistant hybrids. </p>
    <p>Woody ornamental trees, such as maples, may begin to show
    early symptoms of Verticillium wilt. Infected branches may
    appear yellow or off color as they wilt and die back from the
    tips. Cankers and split bark may develop on damaged portion.
    Cut into the wood at the base of wilting branches and look
    for brown or green-brown discoloration. This streaking of the
    sapwood is diagnostic of verticillium wilt. Prune out dead
    branches until all streaking is gone and keep well watered
    during drought. Use mulches to conserve soil moisture. If you
    lose a tree, consider replanting with a more resistant maple,
    such as paperbark or red maple. Norway and Japanese maples
    are more commonly affected. </p>
    <p>There are two kinds of borers that attack the <i>Prunus</i>
    species, which includes flowering cherry, plum, cherry
    laurel, almond, and peach trees. The lesser peach tree borer
    larvae are found under bark in tree crotches and upper
    branches. There are two overlapping generations per year with
    egg hatch occurring from May to mid October. The greater
    peach tree borer larvae are found under the bark in the trunk
    at or below ground level. There is one generation per year
    occurring from June to October. Gummosis and sawdust are
    often associated with and exude from the attack sites. Use of
    nematodes packaged in a product called BioSafe can be applied
    to the bark as a spray any time borer larvae are present, the
    temperature is between 60-85 degrees, and the site is not
    clogged by hardened gummosis. Use of a systemic insecticide
    may also be applied to holes if nematodes are not used. Since
    borers are attracted to wounded areas, take care to prevent
    wounds from lawn mowers, weed eaters, or improper pruning
    cuts. </p>
    <p>Potato plants may be heavily attacked by Colorado potato
    bettles this month. Adult beetles are yellow with black
    stripes. Eggs are orange and are laid in rows on the
    undersides of leaves. Hand pick adults or leaves with eggs to
    control. </p>
    <p>Squash vines that have succumbed to sudden wilting may
    have squash vine borers in their stems. Borers enter into the
    base of the stems in early summer to feed. It is sometimes
    effective to slit the stem to remove the borer, then cover
    soil back over the damaged stem. You can escape damage by
    planting a second crop late in the month. The vine borer's
    life cycle will have been completed before posing a threat to
    your new crop. </p>
    <p>Striped cucumber beetles feed on beans, corn, cucumbers,
    peas, and squash plants. The adult is distinguished by yellow
    wing covers with three black longitudinal stripes and a black
    head. It's partner in destruction is the spotted cucumber
    beetle, recognized by its yellow-green wing covers and black
    spotted back. Both beetles transmit bacterial wilt and
    cucumber mosaic, which can be fatal. Control larvae in the
    soil that feed on the roots and stem with nematodes. Control
    adults by covering plants with floating row covers or
    cheesecloth as soon as the plants push through the ground. </p>
</blockquote>

<p><font color="#804000"><em><strong>Scott Aker National
Arboretum </strong></em></font></p>

<p><font color="#804000"><b><i>© 1996 InSync Publishing. All
rights reserved. <br>
No material may be reprinted without written permission from the
publisher.</i></b> </font></p>

