<head>
<title>The Earth 78-95: Organic Insect Pest Control</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body background="../graphics/backgrd5.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
link="#FF0000" vlink="#800080">

<h1><font color="#FF0000"><font size="6">THE</font></font><font
size="6"> EARTH </font></h1>

<blockquote>
    <h2><font size="5">Organic Insect Pest Control</font><font
    color="#FF0000"> <br>
    <font size="4"><i>by Sylvia Ehrhardt</i> </font></font></h2>
</blockquote>

<blockquote>
    <p>A healthy garden with sturdy, well-nourished plants and
    fertile soil is the best insurance against the arrival of
    pests. The way to fight insects is to prevent them in the
    first place. </p>
    <p>But sometimes no matter how careful you are, harmful
    insects strike your vegetables with a vengeance. Controlling
    these insects in a manner that is gentler on the natural
    ecosystem and which does not leave toxic residues is very
    important. Re-establishing the natural balance of pest and
    predator species in the garden is the role of the gardener. </p>
    <p>The first line of defense is a healthy soil which will
    grow healthy plants. Insect pests function to cull weak and
    poorly nourished plants. The basis of all plant health is
    what you feed the soil, not what you feed the plant. There is
    a connection between how well you prepare the soil and the
    vigor of the plants. There is also a relationship between the
    vigor of the plant and its resistance to pests. When plants
    are growing at their best, they are better able to ward off
    insect pests, thus making pests a minor problem. </p>
    <h3>Here are some general tips:</h3>
    <ul>
        <li>Prevent the plants from being under stress. Plants
            under stress attract insect pests. </li>
        <li>Make sure the plants get enough water. </li>
        <li>Keep the soil moist and soil temperature even by
            mulching with straw or grass clippings. </li>
        <li>If your plants need a boost or are under stress,
            fertilize with a liquid plant food - fish, kelp or
            compost tea can be used. Kelp is especially good for
            stressed plants. </li>
        <li><b><i>Have good cultural practices.</i></b> </li>
        <li>Keep the garden clean; it's important to pick fruit
            off the ground to prevent larva from getting into the
            soil to complete its life cycle. </li>
        <li>Have the garden weed free so that the insect pests do
            not have a place to hide. </li>
        <li>Cover the soil, as much as possible, with a mulch or
            a floating row cover to act as a barrier that will
            slow or stop insects. </li>
        <li>Grow plant varieties that are accustomed to the
            region and will be more resistant to insects. </li>
        <li>Make sure the soil has good drainage so that the
            roots can penetrate freely. Soggy roots make weak
            plants. </li>
        <li>Rotate crops to interrupt the build-up of specific
            plant pests. </li>
    </ul>
    <h3>Organic Pest Controls</h3>
    <p><strong><i>A. Traps that attract insect pests are highly
    effective in reducing the population.</i></strong><strong> </strong></p>
    <ul>
        <li>Japanese beetle traps lure beetles to a bag where the
            beetle cannot escape. </li>
        <li>Yellow sticky traps are good indoors as well as out.
            The yellow color attracts white flies to the sticky
            paper. </li>
        <li>Pheromone traps have aromatic sex attractant of the
            species that calls the insect, then traps it. </li>
    </ul>
    <p><strong><i>B. Repellent flowers and herbs deter insects by
    confusing them.</i></strong><strong> </strong></p>
    <ul>
        <li>Marigolds, tansy, garlic and onions do an excellent
            job. </li>
        <li>Companion planting also is very helpful. </li>
    </ul>
    <p><strong><i>C. Beneficial Insects (predators and parasites)
    can be highly effective in keeping pest populations in check.</i></strong><strong>
    </strong></p>
    <ul>
        <li>Trichogramma wasp thrive on eggs of corn borer and
            prevent the eggs from hatching. </li>
        <li>Pedio wasps lay their eggs in the Mexican bean
            beetles larvae and destroy the larvae. </li>
        <li>Lady bugs, praying mantis, lacewings, assassin bugs,
            yellow jackets, as well as bats, frogs, and birds all
            keep the pest population down. </li>
    </ul>
    <p><strong><i>D. Biological Sprays control specific pests
    without destroying helpful insects as well.</i></strong> </p>
    <ul>
        <li>Milky spore is used to eliminate the Japanese beetle
            grub. </li>
        <li>Bacillus Thuringiensis - (BT), sold as Dipel or
            Thuricide, is a disease that works on many insects
            that pass through the caterpillar stage by paralyzing
            their stomach. </li>
        <li>BT San Diego controls the Colorado potato beetle. </li>
        <li>BT Israelensis controls the mosquito and the black
            fly larvae. </li>
    </ul>
    <p><strong><i>E. Botanical Sprays are made from plants with
    broad pest-killing properties. They degrade quickly and leave
    no residue.</i></strong><strong> </strong></p>
    <ul>
        <li>Pyrethrum is made from the chrysanthemum flower and
            has superior &quot;knockdown&quot; capability. It
            only lasts for four hours. </li>
        <li>Neem is a new insecticide from a tree in Africa. </li>
        <li>Rotenone is made from the roots of a tropical plant.
            It lasts a few days, but has a limited number of
            insect pests that it kills. </li>
        <li>Ryania makes insects too sick to eat. </li>
        <li>Sabadilla seeds come from a South American lily and
            are very effective on squash and harlequin bugs, and
            cucumber beetles. </li>
    </ul>
    <p><strong><i>F. Homemade Sprays are good deterrents. Here is
    a recipe:</i></strong><strong> </strong></p>
    <ul>
        <li>4 whole garlic cloves, 10 large onions, 8 tablespoons
            hot red pepper, 1 gallon water - blend - add 1 cup
            mild liquid soap. Use 1/2 cup of this brew to one
            quart of water and douse the plants. </li>
    </ul>
    <p><strong><i>G. Other methods that can be used.</i></strong><strong>
    </strong></p>
    <ul>
        <li>Dormant oils are very effective in smothering mites
            without harming mite predators. </li>
        <li>Insecticidal soap, made from fatty acids derived from
            plant and animal sources, can suffocate insect pests.
        </li>
        <li>Diatomaceous Earth (DE) is the shell of one-celled
            plants called diatoms that are cracked to expose
            microscopic needles of silica. These needles puncture
            and kill soft bodied pests. Safe to use around pets. </li>
    </ul>
    <p>Can you get rid of chemical pesticides on fruits and
    vegetables? <b>Washing and peeling fruits and vegetables
    &quot;does not remove or decrease the number of pesticides
    present in the food&quot;, according to an analysis of
    government data on pesticide residues done by the
    Environmental Working Group</b>. That is why it is important
    to find other ways in which to repel or control insect pests.
    </p>
</blockquote>

<p><a href="../sylvia/index.htm"><font color="#FF0000"><strong><i>Sylvia
Ehrhardt</i></strong></font></a><font color="#FF0000"><strong><i>
conducts training programs at the Ehrhardt Organic Farm for
students interested in organic agriculture. (301) 834-7520</i></strong><strong>.</strong></font></p>

<p><font color="#FF0000"><b><i>© 1996 InSync Publishing. All
rights reserved. <br>
No material may be reprinted without written permission from the
publisher.</i></b> </font></p>

