<html>

<head>
<title>To Do: July &amp; August's Garden</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body background="../graphics/backgrd5.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
link="#800000" vlink="#800080">

<h1><font color="#FF8000"><font size="6">TO</font></font><font
color="#000000"><font size="6">DO</font></font><font size="6"> </font></h1>

<blockquote>
    <h2><font size="5">July &amp; August's Garden</font> <font
    color="#008000"><em><br>
    </em></font><font color="#FF8000"><font size="4"><em>by
    Sherry Kitchen</em></font></font></h2>
    <p><img src="../graphics/summer.jpg" align="bottom"
    width="260" height="214"></p>
    <p>Stay out of the midday heat, now is the time to really
    appreciate the shade garden and cooler evening hours before
    sundown. Save any replanting for a forecast of rain or a
    prediction of several cloudy days to give your transplants a
    chance to adjust. Sometimes I will not plant in a full sun
    location till fall rather than subject the transplant to July
    &amp; August blasts of sun combined with drought. </p>
    <p>Groom the beds of old blooms and yellow leaves.
    Deadheading can prolong the blooming cycle. </p>
    <p>Mulch garden after a soaking rain to hold in moisture. </p>
    <p>Pick vegetable produce daily. Now all the hard work is
    paying off with garden fresh foods daily. </p>
    <p>If you want to rejuvenate a flower bed, attack a small
    section at a time preferably after a good rainfall when weeds
    are easily pulled. I pick an area that's shaded and try to
    quit when the sun comes around. Don't bite off too much at
    one time. It's much more satisfying to actually <b>finish</b>
    a small area. Replace and rebuild the soil each time you
    plant by working in some leaf mold, compost, or cow manure.
    If you can handle the digging, edging a bed makes a big
    visual difference especially from a distance. </p>
    <p>Replant seeds for fall harvest of lettuce and other cool
    weather crops like kale, collards, and broccoli. Fall weather
    is prefect for growing these. </p>
    <p>If some of your plants are suffering from mildew, instead
    of spraying you can try improving the air circulation and cut
    back the damaged areas. Large shrubs can't be moved but
    trimming away the powdery foliage will perk up the plant and
    increase circulation. Annual removal of 1/3 of the old
    branches is suggested on mature shrubs. Lilacs are especially
    prone to mildew, pruning, good air circulation and plenty of
    sun seems to help. Silica has proven itself to be an
    effective preventive against mildew and other fungal growths.
    Try a foliar feed of horsetail tea or consider broadcasting
    granite dust (67% silica) or Greensand (50% silica) to reduce
    growth of fungi on the soil and to promote healthy plants
    from the ground up. </p>
    <p>Change the water in your birdbath daily to prevent
    development of mosquito larvae. Empty pots and saucers with
    standing water, these are also breeding grounds. </p>
    <p>If the weather stays dry, let the grass go dormant till
    rains return. If you must have green grass, water early in
    the morning. </p>
    <p>Drying herbs and flowers is a summer morning activity. If
    you do this on dry days after the dew has dried your results
    will be better. </p>
    <p>Continue cutting mums up till the second week of July.
    Stop then so that the plants will have time to bud for fall. </p>
    <p>It's time for lots of butterflies again. They will be
    hatching or laying eggs on host plants for the next few
    months. If you notice all the foliage on some plants
    disappearing in one day, it may be that the eggs hatched and
    they're hungry. </p>
    <p>Your container plants may need daily watering especially
    if the pots are exposed to the drying sunlight. Consider
    nesting the pot in a shadier spot when the summer sun is the
    hottest. </p>
</blockquote>

<p><a href="../flora/index.htm"><font color="#FF8000"><b><i>Sherry
Kitchen</i></b></font></a><font color="#FF8000"><b><i> has a
fairly unkempt garden. She's also very jealous of the Deer who
get to spend much more time there than she does.</i></b></font></p>

