<html>

<head>
<meta http-equiv="Content-Type"
content="text/html; charset=iso-8859-1">
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 2.0">
<title>From The Editors Desk - Dig Magazine 10/95</title>
</head>

<body background="../graphics/backgrd5.gif">

<p><font size="6" face="Brush Script MT">From the</font><font
color="#800000" size="6" face="Brush Script MT"> Editors</font><font
size="6" face="Brush Script MT"> Desk</font><font size="6"> </font></p>

<blockquote>
    <p><img src="../graphics/writers/sk2b.jpg" width="240"
    height="209"></p>
    <h2><font size="4"><em><strong>Dear Readers</strong></em></font>,
    </h2>
    <p>The rains came. I do wish I had gotten my new purchases in
    the ground before it started. These damp cool evenings have
    greened the landscape and lawn after months of hot, dry
    weather. Though a complete revival has not yet occurred in my
    garden, it's close. As the amount of daylight drops the mum
    buds swell. Some of my mums bloom as early as July, but the
    full flush of color always waits till after the arrival of
    fall. When their rich color along with the smell of damp
    fallen leaves and rotten apples overtakes my yard, autumn's
    arrival will be complete. Now if it doesn't get too cold too
    quick, we can all enjoy a long fall planting season. I'll
    need as long as possible to get my planting done. </p>
    <p>Big news! This month we welcome <b>Peter Loewer</b>, a
    renowned writer and illustrator, who contributes his insight
    on creating a woodland garden for pleasure and wildlife. His
    recommended choices will add variety to your landscape. Why
    not start a new plan now? Many do not let a fall season past
    without planting at least one new mum, so we've provided some
    helpful suggestions to make them perennials in your garden.
    Have you noticed a new rose at area garden centers this
    season? Introductory promotion of the <b>`Flower carpet'</b>
    rose boasts of its hardy resistance to the common plague of
    hybrid teas: black spot. The color is vibrant pink and worth
    a test in any garden. If you face the dilemma of surplus
    harvest from your food garden, Sylvia offers options on the
    `what and how' of storage. You know fall and early winter are
    the optimum time for tulip planting. If you want to extend
    your bloom season, give Joann's triple-decked planting method
    a try. </p>
    <p><b>So you don't feel like planting anything</b>&#151;
    maybe a stroll through the old meadow in Fern Valley at the
    National Arboretum will renew your spirit. You'll most likely
    leave wanting to bring its peacefulness home with you.
    Walking through a garden imparts a glimpse of the energy of
    its creator. Catch <b>Jacqueline Heriteau's</b> glimpse of
    the great spirit of Jefferson's Monticello. </p>
    <p><i>Enjoy the season,</i> </p>
    <p><img src="../graphics/writers/sksig.gif" width="108"
    height="66"> </p>
</blockquote>

<blockquote>
    <p><a href="../flora/index.htm"><b>Sherry Kitchen</b></a>, <i>editor</i>
    </p>
</blockquote>

