<html>

<head>
<title>Uninvited Guests: When Bambi Gets Into Your Garden</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body background="../graphics/backgrd5.gif">

<h1><font color="#FF0000"><font size="6">UNINVIT</font></font><font
size="6">ED GUESTS </font></h1>

<blockquote>
    <h2><font size="5"><em><strong>When Bambi Gets Into Your
    Garden<br>
    </strong></em></font><font size="4"><em><strong><i>by Sherry
    Mitchell</i></strong></em></font></h2>
</blockquote>

<blockquote>
    <p><img src="../graphics/deer2.gif" align="bottom"
    width="150" height="152">Anyone who knows me, knows that I
    love plants and animals and create garden sanctuaries that
    are not only hospitable to humans, but inviting to the
    surrounding wildlife. We've had many &quot;wild
    encounters&quot; in years past, but our pleasant existence
    between man and nature was finally broken by the deer. </p>
    <p>One fall evening they arrived and ate their way through
    the garden I had so lovingly created. Yarrow, shasta daisies,
    pansies, globe thistle, and mallow all quickly disappeared.
    By winter, the 'Blue Stallion', 'Blue Princess', and 'Blue
    Prince' hollies along the front yard hedgerow began to get
    smaller and smaller. It was as if I had put out a neon sign
    that read, &quot;Good Eats.&quot; </p>
    <p>It's no secret that deer are a serious problem in the area
    and they are sighted regularly by many local homeowners. The
    rapid growth of office and residential development of former
    woods and farmland has acted to drive deer from their
    habitat. Again and again, deer are forced to coexist with
    humans, sometimes with serious consequences to auto owners,
    farmers, gardeners, local game wardens, and the deer
    themselves. The deer population in our region has exploded
    with numbers in the hundreds of thousands. Virginia alone
    reports an estimated 800,000 to 1 million animals. With
    diminishing habitat and no natural predators, their numbers
    have skyrocketed. Suburban gardens are often the targets of
    hungry deer, much to the dismay of homeowners in the region.
    Deer relish such ornamental plants as roses, azaleas, yews,
    clematis, tomatoes, firs, pansies, and apple trees. When
    hungry enough they will even turn to holly, forsythia,
    viburnums, and spiraea. </p>
    <p>Deer do their damage in three ways, by browsing foliage,
    buds, flowers, and twigs of plants; by rubbing their antlers
    on bark of small trees; and by trampling plants. Deer have no
    upper incisors and must jerk or tear plants, leaving a ragged
    end. On the other hand, a clean cut usually means that a
    rabbit or groundhog is the culprit. </p>
    <p>Homeowners do have a few solutions. Fencing is the most
    effective, but least practical solution for suburbanites.
    Electric shock fences are great, but these aren't cost
    effective or safe in residential neighborhoods. For a
    stationary, non-shock type of fence to work, it must be at
    least eight feet high and close to the ground so that deer
    cannot crawl under it. Of course, any type of fence must be
    checked regularly and maintained to be effective. Deer
    constantly test fence lines and if they find they can
    penetrate, the barrier will lose its effectiveness. </p>
    <p>Planting plants that deer will not eat is also an option.
    But when hungry, there are very few plants that ravenous deer
    will totally avoid. Since plants, like foxgloves and
    daffodils, are toxic, the deer seem to sense this and leave
    them alone. Plants like barberry, pieris, boxwood, inkberry,
    mugo pine and spruce are beautiful and rarely eaten by deer,
    but what if you have a passion for perennials, or want to
    grow champion roses? </p>
    <p>Home remedies such as bags of human hair, tiger dung, and
    bars of soap hung from the shrubs are conspicuous and their
    effectiveness questionable. Dogs on patrol also ward off
    deer, but are useless if kept indoors at night. </p>
    <p>Dozens of repellents, however, have recently hit the
    market. While not eliminating the damage, repellents such as
    Ropel, Deer Away, and Hinder can severely reduce browsing by
    changing the behavior of the deer. Repellents are cheaper
    than fencing and invisible to the eye, but require more work
    on the part of the homeowner. Time and weather wear away most
    repellents, so they need constant renewal. Still, using
    repellents with a taste or odor that deer dislike has become
    the most popular damage control method to date. </p>
    <p>Unfortunately, the urban deer problem isn't going to go
    away. It's most saddening for those of us who love our garden
    plants and the wildlife that a garden invites. I wish all our
    visiting wildlife could be accommodated, but in order to keep
    the home-grounds thriving for everyone, the deer must be
    encouraged to dine elsewhere. </p>
</blockquote>

<p><font color="#FF0000"><em><strong><b><i>Sherry Mitchell is a
garden writer and naturalist living in Virginia. On dealing with
deer in your backyard some helpful hints can be provided by your
local cooperative extension office.</i></b></strong></em><em><strong>
</strong></em></font></p>

<p><font color="#FF0000"><em><strong>© 1995 InSync Publishing.
All rights reserved. <br>
No material may be reprinted without written permission from the
publisher. </strong></em></font></p>

