<head>
<meta http-equiv="Content-Type"
content="text/html; charset=iso-8859-1">
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 2.0">
<title>Holidays at Mount Vernon</title>
</head>

<body background="../graphics/backgrd5.gif">

<h1><font size="6" face="Arial Black">Mount Vernon:</font></h1>

<blockquote>
    <h2><font color="#0080C0" size="4"><em><strong>Moonlight
    Tours and an Old Fashion Christmas</strong></em></font><font
    color="#0080C0"> </font></h2>
    <table border="0" cellpadding="4" width="80%">
        <tr>
            <td valign="top">Step back in history and enjoy the
            18th-century sights, sounds and scents of the holiday
            season at George Washington's plantation home. The <b>&quot;Holidays
            at Mount Vernon&quot;</b> program is held daily from
            December 1 through January 6, 1996, including
            Christmas and New Year's Day. In the Mansion, guides
            will introduce guests to the custom of the
            &quot;Christmas Pye,&quot; describe Washington's
            family holiday traditions and direct visitors to the
            rarely-seen third floor. Outside, guests are welcomed
            around a bonfire for complimentary cookies and hot
            cider. This year, the Holiday program opens with <b>&quot;Mount
            Vernon by Moonlight</b>&quot; - a special week of
            evening candlelight tours - <i>marking the first time
            ever that the Mansion is open to the public after
            dark. </i>&quot;Mount Vernon by Moonlight&quot;
            evening tours of the Mansion will be offered December
            1 - 5, between 5 p.m. and 8 p.m. During this evening
            program, visitors will meet with re-enactors of
            historic characters from Washington's time, dressed
            in period clothing, as they are escorted throughout
            the candlelit home of George Washington. On the
            grounds, guests are invited to enjoy caroling,
            cookies and hot orange &quot;wassail&quot; around a
            blazing bonfire. Also during the &quot;Mount Vernon
            by Moonlight&quot; evening tour, visitors will take
            home a &quot;Holiday Surprise&quot; (while supplies
            last) when visiting Mount Vernon Inn Gift Shop and
            Christmas Corner. <p>Mount Vernon's Holiday program
            emphasizes 18-th century hospitality. As winter
            slowed the pace of farming and outdoor activities at
            Mount Vernon, Christmas was a time to enjoy family,
            friends and the spirit of the holiday season.
            Visitors will see a dinner table featuring the
            &quot;Christmas Pye&quot; (main course contained in a
            thick pastry crust and consisting of spiced fowl,
            game, birds and meats) and a plethora of other meats,
            vegetables and dessert trays awaiting holiday guests.
            Patterned after a winter meal served at Mount Vernon
            in 1798, this Holiday table is an authentic
            representation of Mount Vernon entertainment. In
            keeping with 18-th century Christmas tradition, the
            Mansion is simply decorated with greenery from the
            estate, and there are no Christmas trees, wrapped
            packages or tinsel to be seen. </p>
            <p>On the grounds, near a replica of George
            Washington's Valley Forge tent, a roaring bonfire
            invites visitors to enjoy the 18th century
            hospitality first hand with volunteers clad in period
            attire serving cookies and hot cider and enjoying
            conservation. </p>
            <p>In keeping with the Washingtons' tradition, the
            doors of George Washington's home will be open on <b>Christmas
            and New Year's Day</b>, making it one of the only
            attractions in America that welcomes guests 365 days
            a year. Winter hours of operation are from 9 a.m. - 4
            p.m. </p>
            <p>Also it's <b>Scouting Months</b> at Mt. Vernon.
            From November 1 until February 17th all <b>boy and
            girl scouts</b> <b>in uniform</b> will be free; and
            special rates for leaders. Troop wreathlaying and
            surveying activities may be scheduled, (<i>reservations
            required)</i>. The 'Historic Scouting Trail' may be
            hiked year-round. For information on Troop Parades,
            wreathlaying and featuring Revolutionary War Soldiers
            call (703) 780-2000, ext. 322. </p>
            </td>
            <td valign="top"><img src="../graphics/mtvern.gif"
            border="1" width="150" height="108"><p>&nbsp;</p>
            <p>&nbsp;</p>
            <p>&nbsp;</p>
            <p>&nbsp;</p>
            <p>&nbsp;</p>
            <p>&nbsp;</p>
            <p>&nbsp;</p>
            <p>&nbsp;</p>
            <p>&nbsp;</p>
            <p>&nbsp;</p>
            <p>&nbsp;</p>
            <p><img src="../graphics/mtvern2.gif" border="1"
            width="200" height="153"></p>
            </td>
        </tr>
    </table>
</blockquote>

<p><font color="#0080C0"><i>Mount Vernon, located at the southern
end of the George Washington Memorial Parkway -- 16 miles south
of Washington, DC - is owned and operated by the Mount Vernon
Ladies' Association. The estate is open to the public every day
of the year. Admission rates are as follows: Adults, $8.00;
Senior Citizens, $7.50; Children (6-11), $4.00; and Children 5
and under, FREE. For year round hours of operation and other
information, please call (703) 780-2000.</i> </font></p>

