<head>
<title>Trees: Return of the Elm</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body background="../graphics/backgrd5.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
link="#008000" vlink="#800080">

<h1><font color="#008000"><font size="6">TREES</font></font></h1>

<blockquote>
    <h2><font size="5">Return of the Elm</font><font
    color="#FF0000"><br>
    </font><font color="#008000"><font size="4"><i>by </i>Russell
    Balge</font></font></h2>
    <p>As a student at the University of Wisconsin during the
    late 50's and off and on again during the 60's, while
    pursuing my B.S. and M.S. degrees, I loved to walk about the
    campus admiring the stately rows of <b><i>Ulmus americana,</i></b>
    the American elm. Gradually though, during the late 60's and
    into the 70's, many of the elms needed to be cut down, one by
    one, despite the heroic efforts of bathing them in
    insecticides, cutting out diseased limbs, and injecting them
    with fungicides. Today, Bascom Hall no longer is a majestic
    avenue of American elms flanking a grassy
    two-to-three-block-long hill leading up to Bascom Hall. The
    culprit of course was a fungal disease, <i>Ceratocystis ulmi</i>,
    Dutch elm disease, which is spread by natural root grafts and
    the feeding activity of bark beetles. Unfortunately, the
    tendency to plant monocultures of American elm did not
    enhance the tree's survival. </p>
    <p>Today, the main treatments remain early detection, strict
    sanitation, and improved fungicide-injection techniques.
    While these methods slow the spread of the disease, they do
    not stop it, and they are reserved for valuable specimens.
    Because not all trees are treated, the disease survives and
    continues to spread to other trees. </p>
    <p>Researchers have worked for many years to develop a
    suitable replacement for the American elm. A few landscapers
    have chosen to use <i>Ulmus carpinifolia</i> `Urban Elm', a
    result of many crosses between <i>Ulmus x hollandica</i> var.
    vegeta x <i>Ulmus carpinifolia</i> x<i> Ulmus pumila</i>.
    This selection is resistant to Dutch elm disease, grows fast
    on various types of soil, has dark green foliage, and is
    tolerant of drought, pollution, soil compaction, and
    restricted root space. While `Urban Elm' sounds like a God
    send, most tree connoisseurs do not consider it as handsome
    as the American elm. </p>
    <p>The Elm Research Institute of Harrisville, NJ, is offering
    a cultivar of American elm,<i> Ulmus americana </i>`American
    Liberty', to the general public, but not the commercial
    industry. The result of extensive cross-breeding of American
    elms at the University of Wisconsin, the cultivar has all of
    the ornamental attributes of the original American elm, and
    is highly resistant to Dutch elm disease. `American Liberty'
    does have one serious drawback. It is susceptible to elm
    yellowing, formerly known as phloem necrosis. </p>
</blockquote>

<p><font color="#008000"><strong><i>by Russell Balge, Regional
Specialist, Western Maryland Research and Education Center,
University of Maryland Cooperative Extension Service</i></strong><strong>
</strong></font></p>

<p><font color="#008000"><b><i>© 1995 InSync Publishing. All
rights reserved. <br>
No material may be reprinted without written permission from the
publisher.</i></b> </font></p>

<p><a href="../home.htm"><img src="../graphics/dig/dighome.gif"
align="bottom" border="0" width="160" height="20"
href="../home.htm"></a> <br>
</p>
</body>
</html>
