<body background="../graphics/backgrd5.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
link="#000080" vlink="#0080C0">

<h1><font color="#808000" size="7" face="Arial Black">net</font><font
color="#000000" size="7" face="Arial Black">.bits</font><font
face="Arial Black"> </font></h1>

<blockquote>
    <h2><font size="5"><strong>Netscape Navigator 2.0</strong></font></h2>
    <p>The newest release of the widely popular Web browser
    (Internet client) Netscape Navigator 2.0, brings a new level
    of interactivity to users on enterprise networks and on the
    Internet. After an extensive beta testing, users can test
    drive the new version by downloading it from Netscape's
    Server (<a href="http://www.netscape.com">http://www.netscape.com</a>).
    </p>
    <p>By combining the capabilities of the World Wide Web,
    electronic mail, threaded discussion groups, chat, and file
    transfer services together in a seamlessly integrated
    package, Netscape Navigator 2.0 lets users access and share
    information within a single, easy-to-use environment.
    Navigator is available in multiple Windows, Macintosh and
    UNIX versions. </p>
    <p>By combining Netscape Navigator with Netscape servers, it
    is now possible to set up secure encrypted corporate internal
    and external communications (see Internet Security). </p>
    <p>Version 2.0 features several ground-breaking features.
    With its support for frames, Netscape continues it's effort
    to extend HTML (<i>the language used to compose Web pages</i>).
    <b>Frames</b> divide the page or screen into regions
    containing information such as tables of contents, static
    information such as banners and ledges, and changing
    information such as display panels. If you are not using 2.0,
    your browser will ignore the frame information (tags), and
    the page will not display properly. Unfortunately, in the
    quest for world domination (i.e., stop Microsoft at any
    cost), many users may be left out in the proprietary cold. </p>
    <p>The game behind the scenes is whether anyone will find
    these new tags necessary, and opt for Netscapes bells and
    whistles versus another's, such as Microsoft's. Microsoft,
    for it's part in this game, has introduced <b>HTML</b> tags
    of it's own that, you guessed it, are only visible when
    viewed from Microsoft's browser, <b>Internet Explorer</b>.
    Here today, Betamax tomorrow! </p>
    <p>A very powerful new feature is 2.0's support for <b>Inline
    Plug-ins</b>, which enable other companies to extend the
    feature set of Navigator. As we went to press, many plug-ins
    have been announced and are available for downloading. Adding
    support for Apple <b>QuickTime</b> movies, Adobe <b>Acrobat </b>PDF
    documents, and Macromedia Director presentations (<b>Shockwave</b>)
    into the Navigator platform, Inline Plug-ins<b> </b>allow
    rich multimedia content to be incorporated into Internet
    sites. Visit INSYNCnet (http://www.insyncnet.com) and check
    out our shockwave file to get a feeling for what these new
    extensions bring to the Web. </p>
    <p>Java support is another exciting feature of 2.0. <b>Java
    applets</b> bring animation, live updating, and two-way
    interaction to the Web. It is envisioned that in the near
    future, many of us will be using $500 Internet boxes
    (clients), that no longer store programs on their hard drive,
    but run programs downloaded from the net- Java programs. </p>
    <p>In short, Netscape Navigator 2.0 is an exciting product,
    and a must for anyone serious about the Internet, the Web,
    and where it's headed. </p>
    <h2>Internet Security</h2>
    <p>When submitting information to any site, you are sending
    information out into the blue. The un-secure blue. There are
    many efforts afoot to implement secure transactions over the
    Internet, and <b>Netscape Navigator</b> (see new release
    information/review in this issue)and <b>Microsoft's Internet
    Explore</b>r are two Web browsers that support these security
    efforts. </p>
    <p>The Internet security technology developed by <b>Netscape
    Communications</b> to ensure private and authenticated
    communications (called <b>SSL</b>, short for Secure Sockets
    Layer protocol) is an open platform put into the public
    domain for the Internet community. Netscape Navigator and the
    Netscape Commerce Server are the first products to offer this
    non-proprietary technology. </p>
    <p>You can enter your credit card number on a secure (https)
    Netscape Navigator form and transmit the form over the
    Internet to a secure Netscape Commerce Server without risk of
    an intermediary obtaining your credit card information. The
    security features offered by Netscape Communications
    technology protects commercial transactions, as well as all
    other communications, from misappropriation and fraud that
    could otherwise occur as information passes through Internet
    computers. </p>
    <p>Secure communications do not eliminate all of an Internet
    user's concerns. For example, you must be willing to trust
    the server administrator with your credit card number before
    you enter into a commercial transaction. Security technology
    secures the routes of Internet communication; security
    technology does not protect you from unreputable or careless
    people with whom you might choose to do business. </p>
    <p>The situation is much like telling someone your credit
    card number over the telephone. You may be secure in knowing
    that no one has overheard your conversation (<b>privacy</b>)
    and that the person on the line works for the company you
    wish to buy from (<b>authentication</b>), but you must also
    be willing to trust the person and the company. </p>
    <p>Server administrators must take additional precautions to
    prevent security breeches. To protect your information, they
    must maintain physical security of their server computers and
    control access to software passwords and private keys. </p>
    <p>Internet merchants know that they have to accept that
    risk. &quot;Clearly the Internet has its flaws in terms of
    being able to communicate over secure circuits,&quot; says
    James E. Coane, president and CEO of Telebase Systems Inc.,
    which developed <b>Music Boulevard</b>
    (http://www.musicblvd.com/), a Web music store and
    information center. &quot;The reality is that the consumer is
    not really at risk because the credit card companies and the
    on-line services realize that if they are not willing to
    accept the risk, we threaten the emergence of the Internet as
    a viable retailing channel.&quot; </p>
    <p>Music Boulevard, which stocks more than 100,000 titles,
    allows consumers to send encrypted credit card numbers to
    their <b>Netscape server</b>, to fax their card information,
    or to call a 24-hour, toll-free phone number. The &quot;vast
    majority&quot; of its &quot;thousands&quot; of customers are
    sending their card numbers over the Net, Coane says. Coane
    adds that the consumer information is instantly and
    completely protected from crackers/hackers, once it reaches
    Telebase. </p>
    <p>Currently several dozen schemes are afoot to make the
    Internet safe for big-time commerce. These systems will also
    make ordering a lot simpler, and will open up the Net to new
    types of transactions. If you're the cautious type you may
    decide to wait, but someday soon it may be indisputably safer
    to shop on-line than it is to use your credit card in a
    department store. </p>
    <h2>Dig Magazine's successful first month on the Web</h2>
    <p>We wish we could thank all of the people who accessed our
    Web site in it's first month, but that would be difficult. We
    had over 15,000 hits on our site (<i>every hypertext
    jump/link that is clicked counts as a hit</i>), with visitors
    dialing in from the <b>United States, United Kingdom, Japan,
    China, Uruguay, Germany, Sweden, Italy, Malaysia, Israel</b>....well
    the list goes on. Needless to say we're glad we made the
    decision to put Dig Magazine online. </p>
    <p>A big thank you also goes out to all of you who joined our
    <b>mailing list</b>, or <b>added an event </b>to the <b>Dig
    Calendar</b> from our website. We've got a lot in store for
    the coming weeks, so if you haven't checked us out, please
    do. If you have, come back from time to time, there will be
    stuff on our Web site not available in print. </p>
    <h2>Space</h2>
    <p><font face="Arial"><b>No matter how vast, how total, the
    failure of man here on earth, the work of man will be resumed
    elsewhere. War leaders talk of resuming operations on this
    front and that, but man's front embraces the whole universe.</b></font>
    </p>
    <p><font face="Arial">Henry Miller (1891-1980), U.S. author.
    Sunday after the War, &quot;Reunion in Brooklyn&quot; (1944).</font>
    </p>
    <p><font size="1" face="Arial">The Columbia Dictionary of
    Quotations is licensed from Columbia University Press.
    Copyright © 1993 by Columbia University Press. All rights
    reserved.</font> </p>
</blockquote>

<p><font color="#808000"><b><i>© 1996 InSync Publishing. All
rights reserved. <br>
No material may be reprinted without written permission from the
publisher.</i></b></font> </p>

