<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF">
<A HREF="/e/search"><IMG ALIGN=RIGHT BORDER=0 SRC="/gif/Search2.gif"></A>
<A HREF="ATN.cgi?+251"><IMG ALIGN=RIGHT BORDER=0 SRC="/gif/Bibliotheque2.gif"></A><H2> AIDS TREATMENT NEWS - Issue #251,  July 19, 1996</H2><br>
<P>
<CENTER>
<A HREF="ATN.cgi?251:3.2"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="/gif/left.gif"></A>
<A HREF="ATN.cgi?251:3.4"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="/gif/right.gif"></A>
</CENTER>
<UL>
<h4>Triple Therapy with AZT and 3TC in Combination with Nelfinavir Mesylate in 12 Antiretroviral-Naive Subjects Chronically Infected with HIV-1.</h4>
<P>
By M Markowitz and others,
#LB.B.6031.
<P>
This trial enrolled 12 patients to test triple combination therapy with the Agouron protease inhibitor nelfinavir. One withdrew due to apparent drug toxicity (grade 4 CPK elevation); all of the other 11 had viral load below the limit of detection (500 copies with the test used) at 12 weeks. These patients entered the trial with a median CD4 count of 253 and a median viral load of 4.91 log (about 81,000 copies). The median starting CD4 count was 253, and the median increase was 98 at 12 weeks.
<P>
<I>
AIDS TREATMENT NEWS <BR>
Copyright 1996 by John S. James.<BR>
P.O. Box 411256 - San Francico, CA 94141<BR>
